Lisa Yu,2026-01-26,I recently reviewed the poor lenovo experience I had but as I've purchased 2 laptops I thought a second review was only fair. I was asked to review the product via email which I did and received a notice to say my review would not be published. They mention it not meeting guidelines but the pictures I attached was of the formal complaint i sent and my returns receipt. Unsurprisingly my returns have reached the warehouse according to Yodel more than a week ago and not only have I not received a refund I haven't even received notice from Lenovo that its been received by them. I doubt I will ever receive a refund.
Rohit Ahuja,2026-01-26,Lenovo brand is worst with an experience of worst service provided by store or customer service.They don't provide home visit in case of any technical issues or manufacturing defect please do 🚫 not buy the product
Nova,2026-01-24,"I am writing this to warn everyone about Lenovo’s absolutely atrocious customer service. If you are thinking about buying directly from their website—DON’T. Buy from Amazon or Best Buy instead.Here is the situation:The Incident: I ordered a 1TB SSD back in October. The package was marked ""Delivered"" by UPS to my mailbox (not my front door), but it was gone immediately. I never received it.The Loss: I am out over $100 (the full value of the item including tax).The Nightmare Support Process: I have been fighting with them for months. I did everything I could to find the package, I even filed a police report on my own initiative, contacted support multiple times, and finally managed to get a ""supervisor"" on the phone today.Their response was insulting. Even though I never got the product, Lenovo refuses to take any responsibility because UPS has a ""Proof of Delivery"" (just a confirmation it was left at the mailbox).Here are the ridiculous things the support agent actually told me (from my call transcript):""Security Lapse at your location"": They explicitly told me that since UPS dropped it off, if it gets stolen, it is a ""security lapse at the location, which is owned by you."" They literally blamed me for the package being stolen from a mailbox.""Contact the Legal Department"": When I asked for a refund, they seriously told me: ""In that case, you will have to contact the legal department... for a stolen package, unfortunately, we're not able to assist."" Imagine telling a customer to contact a legal department over a $100 SSD.The ""Return"" Excuse: At one point, they even cancelled my case because they claimed ""the package was never dropped off for the return."" I never had the package to return in the first place!Comparison: If this happened on Amazon, I would have had a refund in 5 minutes. Lenovo makes you wait 3 months just to tell you it’s your fault your package was stolen and keeps your money.TL;DR: Lenovo Canada denied my refund for a stolen package. They claimed a ""security lapse"" at my home is my problem and told me to lawyer up. My money is gone. Avoid Lenovo.com at all costs."
Anna,2026-01-23,"I am extremely disappointed with Lenovo UK. I purchased a laptop in late November 2025 as a gift. It was supposed to be delivered on 8 December, but it never arrived.​Despite having written confirmation from UPS that the package was lost/stolen (it vanished after being scanned with an agency driver), Lenovo is refusing to take responsibility. I have been contacting their ""Customer Support"" for weeks. Every single time, I am met with the same scripted response: ""Please allow 3-5 business days for an update"".​It has now been nearly two months. Lenovo has my money, and I have no laptop. They are hiding behind ""internal investigations"" while ignoring my consumer rights. Their social media support is equally useless, offering private messages that lead to more stalling instead of solutions.​If you value your money and time, avoid Lenovo. They are happy to take your payment but will leave you stranded if their courier loses your order. Absolute nightmare."
Victoria Dee,2026-01-23,"I purchased a Lenovo computer for my 89 year old mother just before Christmas as a gift for her. She was unexpectedly put into care and as I was just outside the return window (which is ridiculous - 5 days!) I contacted Lenovo customer service. The computer was brand new, still in it's box and now selling for more than what I paid. Lenovo customer service was unhelpful and in fact rude. I kept getting the same robotic answers from the agent, in fact at one point I asked if I was talking to AI. I even contacted their CIO directly with no response. Will never buy from them again. Would be really nice if someone from Lenovo would actually respond."
Crypticmiss,2026-01-23,Bought Lenovo ideapad3 and it has been nothing but trouble from day one.  Not responsive when installing Windows then very slow downloading anything. Not intuitive and found it impossible to sort out discrepancy with warranty using Lenovo Bridge as it would not download and I tried.  I am hoping I can return it and get a refund as it is impossible to use.  I have had it a week and experienced nothing but frustration with it.
Maddi Newman,2026-01-23,"I live in BC Canada. I ordered my Lenovo mini computer November 23, 2025. Today is January 22 and I still have not received it. Multiple calls have given me nothing but ""we will escalate..."" ""we are sorry"" ""thank you for your patience"" ""call back in 24 to 48 hours"" ""we will email you within 24 to 48 hours"" ""our manager is not available to speak with you"" ""please hold."" etc.I am being relentless. Asking for immediate email confirmation of their promises (which I've only gotten twice). They have an inability or unwillingness to answer really simple questions, like: ""do your records show that you have already 'escalated my case and promised to get back to me in 24 to 48 hours 3 times?'"" ""Can you tell me when I can expect something to happen?"" ""When I call you back, if you still cannot give me information, what is my next step--call you back again?"" ""Is there anything I can do besides continue to call you back?""I don't yell, I don't swear. I keep my voice calm and I'm courteous. I tell them I understand they have to read their scripts, and ask how can I get some information that isn't in their scripts. I understand that they are only doing what they are permitted to do. ""Is there anyone else I can talk to?"" That just seems to frighten them. I feel like they are as much corporate victims as I am.On one call I ended the conversation by asking him to confirm my understanding of the summary of the half-hour call: that he was unable to do anything right now and that I must call him back in 24 to 48 hours. He confirmed. So I said okay, goodbye. He replied: ""is there anything else I can help you with today?"" (I nearly broke down crying at that point.) I decided to tell him the irony of what he'd just said (""you've just finished telling me there is nothing you can do for me. Why are you asking if there is anything you can do for me?"") before delicately hanging up.Does anyone think these poor folks earn more than minimum wage? I'm ready to go to CBC's ""Go Public."" a program which profiles poor customer service or other corporate cheating.I don't blame those poor phone workers. This is corporate policy I'm on about! The company has locked customers out of contact with anyone but these poor creatures with their limited scripts. No one there cares if I get my computer or not.I'm reading in some of the posts here that getting a refund is a massive undertaking. Lenovo is supposed to be shipping me a replacement--which I can apparently return for a refund if I don't want it. Because it has been 2 months now, I certainly don't expect any customer service should I need it (if I ever get this computer.) Maybe it's wise to just return it unopened and get something else from a reliable company. However, now I'm worried I'll be chasing the money for a year if I go that route. Lenovo is deliberately leaving me nowhere to go with this.At this stage I still don't know if or when I will get my computer (over $950 charged to my credit card on Nov 23.)"
N Mit.,2026-01-23,"To be fair, I like my laptop from an aesthetic perspective, but Lenovo's anti-consumer warranty practices need to be called out. Highly advise against purchasing their extended warranty. Go through a reputable extended warranty company instead. I bought ultimate warranty support, spending extra to extend my warranty beyond the normal 1 year manufacturer warranty. In the second year of owning my laptop a small 1 mm cylinder on a thin plastic clip under my space bar failed. This caused the space bar to be unusable. The repair should be considered under warranty, as normal use should not result in keyboard parts breaking. Basically, using cheap plastic clips is a defect in the design and a material issue. Customer Service tried to say it was accidental damage and since I did not spend an extra $45 on an upgraded warranty above ultimate, I had to pay out of pocket. I had to explain to them that a radio that falls a part in a car during year 2 is a result of material defect when it was used normally, not accidental damage. Similarly, a keyboard that starts to fall apart in the second year of use similarly would fall under the category of a material defect. No matter what they still said it was accidental damage, even though the website covering accidental damage highlights it kicks in when multiple parts break, not a single 1 mm plastic cylinder. They ""graciously"" gave a one time exemption for repair. 3 weeks have gone by without repair for what is supposed to be a next business day warranty repair. Outside of these shenanigans and chicanery, they also maintain practices that go against the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act from 1975, namely: They force you to use a specific company for warrantied items (they refused to send me the keyboard replacement directly), which is against the directives in that act that support ones right to repair (themselves or at a repair tech of their choice). They also still include those stupid ""warranty void if removed"" stickers that the 1975 act also makes invalid. Not to long ago Asus, Gigabyte and other PC parts makers received FTC letters directing them to stop using those stickers, but looks like they missed Lenovo. To add, the tech repair company they use sends an automatic ""We attempted to reach you"" email, with no actual attempt to reach you, once they receive the case from Lenovo (which might be 2 weeks after Lenovo says they opened your repair case). The dispatch for this company is in India, so good luck if you have issues with them. Overall, trying to hide behind an accident protection warranty seems to be the trend for technology companies. You can look over at Dell's site and see they call out keyboards specifically for theirs. These warranty options just are additional cash grabs from the companies and a means to avoid dealing with poor manufacturing practices that reinforce planned obsolescence."
Dimitris Gravanis,2026-01-22,"​I am sharing this to document the total failure of Lenovo and their chosen logistics partner, UPS Switzerland.I purchased a device based on a ""Guaranteed End of Day"" delivery for 21.01.2026. I took a full day off work to be home for the mandatory signature, yet no delivery was attempted. UPS falsely recorded a ""missed delivery"" despite me being present the entire time. No doorbell was rung, and no contact was made.​When I contacted support, a UPS agent named Franco lied and guaranteed a redelivery by 19:00 that never happened. To resolve this failure, I traveled 45 minutes from Zurich to the facility in Bülach today after being led to believe I could pick up the parcel myself. Upon arrival, a hostile and unprofessional staff member refused to release my property, claiming it was ""in a container"" for a supposed delivery tomorrow and could not be unloaded.​Lenovo’s response has been pathetic. Their support offered a 5% partial refund as ""compensation"" for two days of lost professional billable hours and the cost of traveling to a remote warehouse. This is an insulting gesture that fails to account for the actual professional loss incurred.​Lenovo is responsible for the companies they hire to represent them. By using a carrier that falsifies records and employs hostile staff, and then offering a token apology, Lenovo has proven they do not value their customers. I have lost two days of work and still do not have the product I paid for. This is a disgrace."
